Source: Codeademy HTML Course

HTML Basics:

<!DocType html>
<html>
<head> <title> browse </title>
</head>

DEFINITIONS:
<head>: Contains metadata about the page that isn't displayed on the action page 
- example: Browser Title Tag

ABSOLUTE LINKS:
Linking to other web pages:
<a> anchor - include text of the link
- external links aka absolute path

href attribute - hyperlink reference
- example: <a href="http://oprah.com"> This is a link to a website </a>

target attribute - how link should open
- example: new tab = _blank
- example: <a <insert attribute>> insert text </a>

RELATIVE LINKS:
- HTML pages are typically stored in root directory on a server
- example: "About page, contact page, etc."
- user relative URL, assuming files are in a centralized place
- example: ./index.html

JUMP TO SECTION WITHIN A PAGE:
- How to jump to a specific place in a web page 
(1) Give the target an id
<p id="top"> Top of the page </p>
<h1 id= "bottom"> Bottom of the page </h1>
- can add an id to any element on a webpage
- target link = string that cntains # of characters & the target element's id
<ol> = ordered list
<ul> = unordered list
- example:
<div id="introduction
<ul>
<a href = "#introduction">INtroduction </a></ul>

IMAGES: 
- example: <a href = "www.website.com" target ="_blank">
- <image src "#" alt="A text"/></a>
- pattern: <a<image/></a>

WHITESPACE: 
- used to visualize relationships between elements (whitespace & indentation)
- whitespace between elements is ignored by the browser
- put each element on their own line to make more read-able

COMMENTS:
<!--->

TABLE: 

<table>
<tr> = table row
<td> = table data (relative to row)
<tb> = table header (relative)
- remember to crate a blank header
table header scope attribute: row, column
example: <th scope ="row"> RowTitle </th>

Data spanning multiple columns via COLSPAN attribute, value in integers
exmaple: <td colspan="2"> out of town </td>

Data spanning multiple rows via ROWSPAN attribute, value in integers
example: <td rowspan="2">work</td>

Table Body: <tbody>
- typically used for large tables
- contains all table data , including headers

Table Header: <thead>
- requires a row

<table>
	<thead>
		<tr>
			<th></th>
		</tr>
	</thread>
	
Table Footer: <tfoot>
- Section of the bootom of the table
exmaple: table sums, differences, and other data results

<tfoot>
	<td> Total </td>
</tfoot>

STYLING TABLES WITH CSS

example: table,th,td{
	border: 1px solid black;
	fomt-family: Arial, sans-serif;
	text align: center;
}	

